API Endpoint Access URL

https://api.pixlab.io/docscan

Get Your API Key & Try DOCSCAN Now ↗

Description

The DOCSCAN API endpoint scan, process and extracts information from virtually all officially issued ID documents including Passports, ID Cards, Driving Licenses, Visas, Birth & Death Certificates from nearly all recognized UN countries ↗. As of this release, over 11,094 ID documents with or without MRZ from more than 197 countries are fully supported. No other KYC platform has achieved such a milestone.

In addition to ID document scanning capabilities, DOCSCAN features an automatic face detection and extraction tool. This feature crops faces from scanned documents and converts binary information such as ID Cards raw images or Passport Machine Readable Zone (MRZ) into JSON-formatted text ready to be consumed by your application. The resulting JSON data includes essential details like full name, issuing country, document number, address, expiry date, etc. prepared for seamless application integration. For practical application, see examples of JSON outputs for processed Passport images or ID card images at the example section below.

Input Passport Specimen (JPEG/PNG/BMP Image)

Extracted ID Holder Information (with automatic face cropping)

  • DOCSCAN is the sole REST API endpoint located at https://api.pixlab.io/docscan needed to perform ID scanning with automatic face cropping.
  • As of this release, over 11,094 ID documents with or without MRZ from more than 197 countries are fully supported.
  • PixLab recommend linking your AWS S3 bucket via the PxLab Console ↗ to ensure that all cropped images and extracted data are directly stored in your bucket, providing complete control over your users data.
  • Explore various code samples below, with additional examples available on the PixLab Github Repository ↗.
  • For handling PDF documents, first convert them to raw images using the PDFTOIMG ↗ API Endpoint, and send the returned image link directly to the DOCSCAN API endpoint using a simple GET HTTP Request.
  • Developers are encouraged to refer to the code samples section & community contributed tutorials section to learn more about integrating DOCSCAN on their existing code bases.

Supported Documents & Countries

DOCSCAN supports a comprehensive range of officially issued ID documents, including but not limited to: Passports, ID Cards (Citizen ID, Resident ID, Immigration Card, Golden ID, etc.), Driving Licenses, Visas, Birth & Death Certificates from nearly all UN-recognized countries. With this release, the API can handle over 11,094 ID documents, with or without Machine Readable Zones (MRZ), from more than 197 countries. HTTP METHODS

GET, POST Request Body ↓

HTTP PARAMETERS

Mandatory Parameters

Fields Type Description
img URL Input image URL (i.e. ID document to be scanned) if a simple HTTP GET method where your media file is already hosted and accessible via URL is being used instead of a more complete POST upload request. If you want to upload your image directly from your application or scripts, then submit a multipart/form-data POST request. Refer to the POST request body section below, the code samples section here, with additional examples available on the PixLab Github Repository ↗ on how to upload your ID document image directly from your application using the POST method for faster processing. If you are mainly dealing with PDF documents, we recommend that you convert them first to raw images using the PDFTOIMG ↗ API Endpoint.
key Hex String Your PixLab API Key ↗. Your API Key ↗ is mandatory in order to authenticate the upcoming request. You can also embed your API Key in the WWW-Authenticate HTTP header and omit this parameter if you want to. Connect to the PixLab Console ↗ to generate your first API key.
type String Type of document going to be scanned if known in advance. As of this release, over 11,094 ID documents with or without MRZ from more than 197 countries are fully supported. The following are the allowed document types strings:
  • passport: Any type of officially issued Machine Readable Document such as Passports or Travel Documents as stated in the ICAO Document 9303 ↗.
  • idcard: Any type of officialy issued government ID card with or without MRZ including but not limited to: Citizen Card ID, Resident ID, Immigration Card, etc. from one of the supported countries.
  • driver_license: Any type of officilaly issued Driver License with or without MRZ from one of the supported countries.
  • visa: Machine-Readable issued Visa (ICAO Document 9303 ↗ part 7).
  • birth_certificate: Any type of officilaly issued Birth Cerificate from one of the supported countries.
  • death_certificate: Any type of officilaly issued Death Cerificate from one of the supported countries.
  • unknown: Set the value to unknown if you are unsure about the type of the ID document being scanned. DOCSCAN is smart enough to isolate the type of the ID using a heurestic approach with the help of Machine Learning. Please note that this feature is only available starting from the Team or Enterprise Plan ↗ due to the heay compute resources it require.
country String Country of origin of the ID document being scanned. You can omit this field for Passports or ICAO Travel documents, or if the country of origin of the document being scanned is unknown in advance (feature only available starting from the Team or Enterprise Plan ↗). As of this release, over 11,094 ID documents with or without MRZ from more than 197 countries are fully supported. The list of supported countries and documents is documneted here.

Optional Parameters

Fields Type Description
facecrop | face-crop Boolean If this parameter is set to false, no face cropping operation will be performed on the provided document, and the face_url field will be set to false.
Please note that, due to Privacy Regulations, for face cropping to function properly, you must connect your own AWS S3 bucket via the PixLab Console ↗. This ensures the scan engine stores all cropped faces in your private S3 bucket, maintaining data storage compliance..
faceblob | face-blob Boolean If this parameter is set to true, return the BASE64 encoding of the cropped PNG image of the extracted face instead of an S3 URL in the face_url object return field.

POST Request Body Guidelines(for using POST over GET)

Allowed Content-Types:

  • multipart/form-data - Use this for direct (local) media file uploads. Refer to this Python script ↗ for a typical implementation.
  • application/json - Use this when your media file is already hosted and accessible via URL.

Example Showcase: The screen capture below illustrates a typical local image upload using a multipart/form-data POST request made via Postman:



Code samples demonstrating how to perform a POST upload request in your preferred programming language can be found in the section below, or on the PixLab Github Repository ↗.

HTTP RESPONSE

application/json: The DOCSCAN API endpoints always return a JSON object for each request, regardless of whether it was executed successfully. The table below lists the fields returned in a typical HTTP response:

Field Type Description
status Integer HTTP status code where 200 indicates success. Any other code indicates an error.
type String Type of the scanned document.
face_url URL Defaults to false unless you connect your AWS S3 bucket via the PixLab Console ↗. This stores the URL of the cropped face image from the scanned document on your own AWS S3 Bucket.
PixLab require storing extracted images directly in your own AWS S3 Bucket by linking it through the PixLab Console ↗ to maintain complete control over user data.
If the optional face-crop field is set to false on the request, no face cropping operation will be done.
If the optional face-png-blob field is set to true on the request, the BASE64-encoded PNG image of the cropped face is returned instead of the S3 URL.
mrz_raw_text String Extracted raw MRZ text from the document (applicable for Passports and Visas only).
fields Object

Depending on the type of the document being scanned (Passport, Driver License, ID Card, etc.), a JSON Object with the following fields is always returned:

  • fullName: The full name of the ID holder as scanned from the uploaded ID document.
  • issuingCountry: The country or organization that issued the document.
  • documentNumber: The unique number assigned to the document by the issuing authority.
  • address: The address of the ID holder as listed on the ID, if available.
  • dateOfBirth: The birth date of the ID holder, typically in YYYY-MM-DD format.
  • dateOfExpiry: The expiration date of the document, typically in YYYY-MM-DD format.
  • sex: The gender of the ID holder (if available), usually represented as 'M' for male, 'F' for female, or 'O' for other.
  • nationality: The nationality of the ID holder, often coded in full country name or ISO 3166-1 alpha-3 format.
  • issuingDate: The date the document was issued, typically in YYYY-MM-DD format.
  • checkDigit: A checksum digit available on Passport document only calculated from other data within the document to verify its authenticity.
  • personalNumber: An optional unique number assigned to the holder by the issuing authority.
  • finalCheckDigit: An optional final checksum digit calculated from all the data on the document to ensure its integrity.
  • issuingState: The state or region that issued the document, if applicable.
  • issuingStateCode: A code representing the state or region that issued the document, if applicable.
  • religion: The religion of the ID holder, if it is included on the document.
error String Error message, present if the status field is different from 200.
